================================================================================
SERVICE NOW — SYSTEM ADMIN (ORLANDO) — EXAM NOTES (CONSOLE FORMAT)
================================================================================

1) COURSE JOURNEY (topics covered)
   - Intro, Platform overview & architecture
   - UI & Branding
   - Lists & Filters, Forms
   - Task Management, Notifications, Knowledge Mgmt
   - Service Catalog, Tables & Fields
   - ACLs, Data Import, CMDB, Integration
   - Events, Update Sets, Platform Stats
   - Scripting, Custom App Dev
   - Final Recap

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2) PLATFORM OVERVIEW & ARCHITECTURE
   - ServiceNow: American company; product = ServiceNow Platform (PaaS / aPaaS).
   - Use cases: IT, HR, Finance, Security — automate manual & repeatable processes.
   - Not just ticketing — an automation platform.

   ARCHITECTURE:
   - Single data model, flexible table schema, reusable components.
   - Multi-instance architecture (ServiceNow) vs multi-tenant (many cloud providers).
     * Multi-tenant: customers' data co-mingled -> potential availability/risk.
     * Multi-instance: each org has isolated instance (unique software stack). Instances
       can communicate but are isolated.
   - High availability: traffic rerouting to redundant servers on outage.
   - Backups: 4 weekly full backups + 6 days of daily differential backups.
     * Backups used for restore and cloning lower environments.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3) SECURITY & AUTHENTICATION
   - Supports: Local DB (username/password), SSO (SAML 2.0 e.g., Okta), LDAP, OAuth 2.0
     (client_id + secret), Digest Token, Multi-Factor (e.g., Google Authenticator).
   - Role-based access controls (RBAC) — grants access to apps/fields.
   - Elevation of roles (temporary elevation e.g., security_admin).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4) PLATFORMS / INTERFACES
   - Three ways to interact with same system of record:
     1. Native UI (desktop browser)
     2. Mobile Apps (Now Mobile, Agent, Onboarding)
     3. Service Portal (SP - advanced self-service UI)
   - Supported browsers: Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Safari.
   - Service Portal URL: add "sp" after domain to access portal.
   - Mobile apps downloadable from iOS/Android stores; configurable by admins.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5) ROLE-BASED ACCESS (components & best practices)
   - Components:
     * User   = individual (stored in User table)
     * Group  = collection of users (team, similar responsibility)
     * Role   = collection of permissions
   - Best practice: assign roles to GROUPS (not to individual users).
     * Easier maintenance: adding/removing users from group changes permissions.
   - Base (out-of-the-box) roles: admin, itil, approver_user, catalog_admin, etc.
   - Self-service users: can log in with no roles; limited actions (raise incident, view catalog).
   - Impersonate: admins can impersonate other users to view their UI/permissions.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
6) UI (Native) — Key elements & navigation
   - Main screen divided into:
     * Banner Frame (top): logo, user menu, global search, chat, help, settings.
     * Application Navigator (left): All / Favorites / History + filter navigator.
     * Content Frame (center): lists, forms, pages.
     * Edge (available in UI15 only).
   - UI versions: UI16 (default) and UI15 (user-switchable via Settings).

   - Banner Frame details:
     * User menu: profile, impersonate user, elevate roles, logout.
     * Global search: searches across tables; results depend on user's access.
     * Settings: theme, accessibility, list/form personalization, notifications.

   - Application Navigator:
     * All: apps/modules available to user.
     * Favorites: starred items.
     * History: recently visited (configurable timeframe).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
7) BRANDING (UI16 config / welcome page)
   - Change via: "UI16 Configuration" (System Properties -> Basic Configuration UI16).
   - Can update: instance name, banner image, color theme, date/time format.
   - Welcome page content configurable (short description, links, login messages).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
8) LISTS & FILTERS (concepts + operations)
   - List = records from a table (e.g., incident list).
   - List elements:
     * Title bar, Filters, Breadcrumbs (shows applied conditions), Columns/Fields.
   - List title menu: view, filters, group by, show (rows per page), refresh, create favorite.
   - List context menu (right/left click on title bar): sort, visual task board, charts, export, import, update selected.
   - List control (settings): set roles for New/Edit/Filter, edit behavior, max rows (show: 10,15,20,50,100).
   - Filters:
     * Build conditions (field / operator / value), Run to apply.
     * Breadcrumbs show applied filters; can remove or modify.
     * Save filters -> name + visibility (Me / Everyone / Group).
   - Views:
     * Create different views (default, mobile, major incident, etc.) to show different columns/fields.
   - Group By:
     * Group list by a column (e.g., state, priority) — quick aggregation.
   - Update Selected / Update All:
     * Bulk update fields on selected/all records on screen.
   - Export options: Excel, CSV, XML, JSON, PDF.
   - XML view: shows full record fields (not only visible columns).
   - Search:
     * Top search (across selected fields).
     * Inline search under column (can be enabled/disabled). Search adds to filter condition.
   - Personalization:
     * Users can personalize columns via Settings -> "Personalize list columns".
   - Templates & Scheduled Templates:
     * Template = pre-fill set of field values for frequent record creation.
     * Toggle Template Bar on form; apply template to auto-populate fields.
     * Schedule templates to create records on schedule.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
9) FORMS (concepts & config)
   - Form = single record display from a table.
   - Form elements:
     * Content frame, Form title (buttons), Form menu, UI Actions (buttons like Save, Submit), Sections, Related Lists (bottom).
   - Create vs Save vs Submit:
     * Submit: save & close the form (redirect back).
     * Save: save but keep form open.
   - Field types:
     * Mandatory (red asterisk) — required to save/submit.
     * Read-only — non-editable fields on the form.
     * Choice fields (drop-downs).
     * Reference fields — refer to records in other tables (caller -> user table, assignment group, etc.)
   - Activity Stream:
     * Work notes / Additional comments -> posted and captured in activity stream (audit trail).
   - Sections:
     * Group related fields (resolution info, related records, notes).
   - Related Lists:
     * Show related records from other tables (task SLAs, security incidents, etc.)
   - Views:
     * Default + custom views (e.g., major incident view shows extra fields).
   - Form Configuration methods:
     1. Form Layout: classic; pick available fields -> selected fields; create simple fields.
     2. Form Design: advanced drag-and-drop designer; create fields, set mandatory/read-only inline.
     - Configure Related Lists via Configure -> Related Lists.
   - After changes: reload form to reflect layout/design changes.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
10) INCIDENT MANAGEMENT (list/form examples)
    - Common modules: Create New, Assigned to Me, All Open, All Incidents.
    - Pre-built OOB filters in modules; modules may have conditions (e.g., active=true).
    - Changing filter condition may change number of records displayed.
    - Priority is derived from impact & urgency (cannot be set arbitrarily if business rule drives it).
    - Use templates to standardize repetitive incident creation.
    - Use copy incident button to duplicate & create new incident from existing record.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
11) FORM & LIST CONFIGURATION (admin/dev options)
    - Configure accessible via right-click title bar -> Configure -> {Form Layout, Form Design, Related List}.
    - List Configure -> List Layout, List Controls, List Calculation.
    - Form Design: drag field types to create custom fields; name fields; set mandatory/read-only.
    - List Layout: add/remove columns, create fields, set default view.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
12) MISCELLANEOUS
    - Impersonation: used to verify end-user views.
    - Personal Developer Instance: demo instance provided by ServiceNow for practice.
    - Edge element: visible only in UI15.
    - Max rows per page on list: 100.
    - History keeps recent items (default ~10 days; configurable).
    - Favorites: create for quick access; can add icon/color.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
13) KNOWLEDGE CHECK (selected Q&A from transcript)
    Q1: Apps visible to user with NO roles?    => Self-service
    Q2: Edge visible in UI15 or UI16?          => UI15
    Q3: Primary way to access platform data?   => Native UI (platform native UI)
    Q4: Should a role be added directly to user? => False (best practice: add to group)
    Q5: What is a role?                        => Collection of permissions
    Q6: Name two baseline system roles.        => admin, itil (examples)
    Q7: Where is user profile located?         => Banner frame
    Q8: Which button saves and closes form?    => Submit
    Q9: Which button copies incident?          => Copy Incident (form menu)
    Q10: Two ways to configure forms?          => Form Layout, Form Design

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
14) EXAM TIPS (quick)
    - Understand differences: Multi-instance vs Multi-tenant.
    - Remember RBAC hierarchy: User -> Group -> Role (assign roles to groups).
    - Know Save vs Submit behavior on forms.
    - Know how to save/share filters & create favorites.
    - Be familiar with Form Layout vs Form Design steps.
    - Practice: impersonation, saving filters, creating templates, bulk update.
    - Know common auth methods (SSO SAML, LDAP, OAuth, MFA).

